# Rectus Abdominis

> The rectus abdominis is the **paired longitudinal muscle of the anterior abdominal wall**, enclosed within the rectus sheath. It is the primary flexor of the trunk.

## 🔗 Bone Attachments
- **Origin**: [[Hip Bone]] (pubic crest + pubic symphysis)
- **Insertion**: [[Sternum]] (xiphoid process) + [[Ribs]] (costal cartilages 5–7)

## 🗂️ Key Information

| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Origin | Pubic crest & symphysis ([[Hip Bone]]) |
| Insertion | Xiphoid process ([[Sternum]]) + costal cartilages 5–7 ([[Ribs]]) |
| Action | Trunk **flexion**; posterior pelvic tilt; increases intra-abdominal pressure; assists forced expiration |
| Innervation | Intercostal nerves T7–T12 (anterior rami) |
| Blood Supply | Superior & inferior epigastric arteries |

## 🔑 Rectus Sheath
Formed by aponeuroses of external oblique, internal oblique, and transversus abdominis:
- **Above arcuate line**: anterior + posterior sheath present
- **Below arcuate line**: all aponeuroses pass anteriorly → posterior sheath absent (only transversalis fascia)

## 🔑 Tendinous Intersections
- 3–4 horizontal bands create the visible "six-pack" appearance
- Fused to the anterior rectus sheath only

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Rectus sheath hematoma** — Inferior epigastric artery injury (coughing, anticoagulation)
- **Diastasis recti** — Midline separation of the two recti (pregnancy, obesity)
- **Rectus abdominis myocutaneous (RAM) flap** — Common reconstructive option in plastic surgery
- **Core stability** — Works with transversus abdominis and multifidus for spinal stability

